WEBVTT

00:00.226 --> 00:07.216
Well, we are going to start a new series this fall called Long Journey Home, Navigating the Wilderness.

00:08.157 --> 00:11.682
You know, every journey has a beginning.

00:12.563 --> 00:22.898
I don't know about you, but I often find myself planning and thinking ahead about trips, weeks and months in advance.

00:23.042 --> 00:25.444
before our car ever leaves the driveway.

00:25.685 --> 00:31.410
I've been researching Airbnbs and tourist attractions and best routes to travel.

00:31.510 --> 00:42.281
And in one sense, you could say that the trip started as soon as I started to research all those different parts of my trip, the routes and the Airbnbs and all of that.

00:43.161 --> 00:48.467
Because those things are all part of the trip becoming a reality.

00:49.808 --> 00:52.050
But you know how it is, there comes that moment

00:52.482 --> 01:02.115
When the trip becomes more than just an idea or a dream or a packing list, there comes the moment that the trip actually begins.

01:03.216 --> 01:09.604
Earlier this summer, I think you know that Burnett and I had the chance to go with a team of 11 others to Uganda.

01:10.305 --> 01:13.169
And we had a great time ministering there with them.

01:13.730 --> 01:17.074
But when the rest of the team headed home back to the States,

01:17.154 --> 01:22.339
Burnett and I detoured, and we went to Gambia and then into Senegal.

01:22.780 --> 01:25.963
And we did that because we wanted to visit our youngest son and his wife.

01:26.023 --> 01:29.847
They've been serving there with Peace Corps and a little village in Senegal.

01:30.588 --> 01:39.056
And the final homeward bound leg of the trip, though, started from this little hotel way out in Gambia.

01:39.096 --> 01:41.499
And I do mean way out in Gambia.

01:42.420 --> 01:44.882
We had this amazing visit with our kids.

01:45.218 --> 01:47.501
But when it was time to go home, I had an idea.

01:48.282 --> 02:03.000
Because I knew that when the moment came that we actually stepped out of the door of our hotel room there in Gambia, that we wouldn't stop traveling until we stepped back in the door of our house in swim.

02:04.762 --> 02:11.570
So when we stepped out of that hotel room, I decided to press the button on the stopwatch on my phone.

02:12.034 --> 02:13.436
And I kept it running.

02:13.636 --> 02:23.511
I kept it running as we walked down this dark, dirt street in this little village trying to get to the bus stop, the bus that would take us all the way back to Banjul.

02:24.372 --> 02:33.947
I kept it running for the six hours that we rode on the bus through these very rough African roads and had the live chicken on the bus with us and every bit of it.

02:35.169 --> 02:38.834
I kept it running as we flew on multiple flights.

02:39.042 --> 02:42.146
every layover that we encountered, I kept the watch running.

02:42.947 --> 03:00.006
I kept it running when we got off the plane at SeaTac, we got back to our car and made the drive back home, and I didn't hit the stop button until we stepped through our front door here in swim, and it said 41 hours, 30 minutes, 13 seconds.

03:01.027 --> 03:02.409
It was a long trip.

03:03.771 --> 03:06.674
Now, there have been lots of planning that had gone on ahead of time.

03:07.042 --> 03:14.130
And there were buses with live chickens and planes with narrow seats and airports with long lines all along the way.

03:14.190 --> 03:24.822
But the crucial starting point of that homework journey happened the moment that we crossed the threshold of that doorway of our little hotel in Gambia.

03:25.983 --> 03:28.666
Now today we're going to start this new 12 week series.

03:29.547 --> 03:35.794
We're going to be looking at the famous journey of the children of Israel out of slavery in Egypt.

03:36.546 --> 03:46.977
on a wilderness trek that took them not 40 hours, but 40 years on their way to a new, divinely promised homeland.

03:48.239 --> 03:50.121
And I have an idea as we're doing this.

03:50.621 --> 03:54.445
I would like to invite you to keep a travel log.

03:55.566 --> 04:00.011
Over the next 12 weeks, we're gonna be looking at some of the highlights of this amazing journey.

04:00.692 --> 04:06.418
And I would like for you to just try and get maybe a little notebook, pad of paper,

04:06.562 --> 04:17.175
and follow along each week as we highlight different aspects of Israel's journey and take some time outside of Sunday morning to read the story for yourself.

04:18.056 --> 04:27.628
And as you're reading it, ponder how aspects of Israel's physical journey might parallel your own spiritual journey.

04:28.610 --> 04:32.534
And as you do that, I'd like for you to write down the connections that you're making.

04:33.716 --> 04:35.378
Ask the Holy Spirit to

04:35.586 --> 04:41.392
use Israel's story in a fresh way to teach you about how he's leading in your life.

04:42.433 --> 04:44.775
And you might even want to take some side trips.

04:45.275 --> 04:48.599
We're not going to be able to hit everything, every part of Israel's journey through the wilderness.

04:48.619 --> 04:52.282
And as you're reading, there may be things that the war kind of brings to mind.

04:52.302 --> 04:59.109
They jump out at you and feel free to go down those bunny trails and see where it takes you, what you learn from it.

05:00.030 --> 05:04.274
And along the way, if you care to, I'd love to hear some of your stories.

05:04.482 --> 05:05.943
Where are you discovering?

05:05.963 --> 05:10.748
Where are the connections that you're making as you think about your life and the journey of Israel?

05:12.630 --> 05:20.498
When we think about the children of Israel and their journey to the promised land, we realize that there were all sorts of things that had preceded it.

05:21.238 --> 05:28.505
There was a long history of people and events that saw God bringing his people into the land of Egypt.

05:29.186 --> 05:31.128
When they first got there, they were honored guests.

05:32.069 --> 05:33.330
But over time,

05:33.442 --> 05:40.349
Ultimately, they were reduced to slaves, reduced to crying out to God for deliverance from their slavery.

05:41.390 --> 05:45.794
And then along came Moses, a man who had a unique journey of his own.

05:46.655 --> 06:01.490
As you know, when he was born, Pharaoh had this rule out that all the male babies of the Israelites were to be put to death because they were worried about an overpopulation of slaves, that the slaves might become more powerful than the Egyptian.

06:01.698 --> 06:03.320
Moses was spared.

06:03.841 --> 06:09.109
Not only was he spared, he was adopted into Pharaoh's household by one of Pharaoh's daughters.

06:09.810 --> 06:16.520
And so he was a man who lived at the height of power and privilege even as an Israelite within Egypt.

06:17.501 --> 06:19.725
And then his life took a dramatic turn.

06:20.566 --> 06:27.516
And he found himself suddenly not at the height of power, but literally living as an outcast on the run for his very life.

06:29.239 --> 06:31.602
But then, called by God,

06:31.970 --> 06:39.120
to return, to go back to his people with this specific assignment of freeing them from their captivity.

06:40.502 --> 06:48.172
And you probably know how the story went, how Moses returned and there were those plagues, the 10 plagues that were poured out by God on the Egyptians.

06:49.093 --> 06:55.382
And yet every time Pharaoh, with a hard heart, refused to release his slaves.

06:57.024 --> 07:01.650
Each of those plagues corresponded to the false gods that Egypt worshiped.

07:02.882 --> 07:09.929
In other words, God was making it clear that his power was greater than all of the false powers that Egypt was trusting in.

07:11.610 --> 07:16.035
Rather than being their helpers, those idols ultimately became their curse.

07:17.836 --> 07:27.265
In one sense, all of those preceding events, the entire 400 years that Israel had been in Egypt, could be seen as part of Israel's journey.

07:28.747 --> 07:32.050
But if you're gonna start a stopwatch on that trip,

07:32.162 --> 07:37.169
that trip through the wilderness, I wouldn't start it until plague number 10.

07:38.371 --> 07:41.615
Prior to that, Pharaoh kept saying, no go.

07:42.596 --> 07:50.608
But when plague 10 struck, Pharaoh finally shouted, go, get out, get out now.

07:52.030 --> 07:58.098
And since that is the point where I'd hit the start button on the stopwatch, let's focus on that this morning and see what we can learn.

07:58.690 --> 08:00.852
I want to take you to Exodus chapter 12.

08:00.872 --> 08:02.995
We're going to look at the first 14 verses.

08:04.937 --> 08:10.483
The Lord said to Moses, and Aaron, in the land of Egypt, this month shall be for you the beginning of months.

08:10.563 --> 08:12.725
It shall be the first month of the year for you.

08:13.686 --> 08:22.095
Tell all the congregation of Israel that on the 10th day of this month, every man shall take a lamb according to their father's houses, a lamb for a household.

08:22.756 --> 08:28.242
If the household is too small for a lamb, then he and his nearest neighbor shall take according to the number of persons.

08:28.482 --> 08:32.626
According to what each person can eat, you shall make your count for the lamb.

08:33.467 --> 08:36.209
Your lamb shall be without blemish, a male, year old.

08:36.630 --> 08:45.999
You may take it from the sheep or from the goats, and you shall keep it until the 14th day of this month, when the whole assembly of the congregation of Israel shall kill their lambs at twilight.

08:47.060 --> 08:52.305
Then they shall take some of the blood and put it on the two door posts and the lentil of the houses in which they eat it.

08:52.965 --> 08:57.970
They shall eat the flesh that night, roasted on the fire with unloving bread and bitter herbs, they shall eat it.

08:58.594 --> 09:01.518
Do not eat any of it raw or boiled in water, but roasted.

09:02.059 --> 09:09.369
As head with its legs and its inner parts, and you shall let none of it remain until the morning, anything that remains until the morning, you shall burn.

09:09.409 --> 09:11.813
In this manner, you shall eat it.

09:12.554 --> 09:19.684
With your belt fastened, your sandals on your feet, and your staff in your hand, and you shall eat it in haste, it is the Lord's Passover.

09:20.965 --> 09:27.154
For I will pass through the land of Egypt that night, and I will strike all the firstborn in the land of Egypt, both man and beast,

09:27.490 --> 09:30.173
And on all the gods of Egypt, I will execute judgments.

09:30.914 --> 09:31.595
I am the Lord.

09:32.336 --> 09:35.040
The blood shall be assigned for you on the houses where you are.

09:35.060 --> 09:37.703
And when I see the blood, I will pass over you.

09:38.264 --> 09:44.572
And no plague will befall you to destroy you when I strike the land of Egypt.

09:44.592 --> 09:46.695
This day shall be for you in Memorial Day.

09:47.456 --> 09:52.803
And you shall keep it as a feast to the Lord throughout your generations as a statute forever.

09:53.223 --> 09:55.506
You shall keep it as a feast.

09:57.570 --> 09:59.152
What a terrifying judgment.

10:00.374 --> 10:01.616
Death on the first board.

10:03.239 --> 10:05.963
And what a strange mode of protection.

10:07.385 --> 10:07.766
A lamb.

10:09.408 --> 10:11.692
Three things I want to draw your attention to this morning.

10:11.712 --> 10:12.814
The first is the dinner.

10:13.715 --> 10:15.298
Second, we're look at the dinner party.

10:15.959 --> 10:18.282
And third, I want to look at the dress code for the dinner.

10:19.304 --> 10:20.466
So the dinner.

10:22.649 --> 10:23.250
A lamb.

10:25.218 --> 10:28.282
What a strange mode of protection if you think about it.

10:29.643 --> 10:43.720
Israel, your protection from the destroyer is going to be a lamb dinner and a bit of blood on the door frame of your house, which doesn't sound like much protection to me.

10:45.221 --> 10:49.106
I would have suggested barring the door with heavy beans.

10:50.050 --> 10:56.518
or boarding up the windows, or sneaking home a wheelbarrow loader to a bricks from the worksite to reinforce the doors in the windows.

10:56.618 --> 11:00.783
I mean, if the destroyer is coming, do something that's going to really protect you.

11:02.786 --> 11:07.952
Not only will the lamb be their protection from death, it's also going to be their key to freedom.

11:09.434 --> 11:19.506
The reason that they were living and breathing and not overwhelmed with grief and funerals when the command to go was given was because they'd been protected by the lamb.

11:21.186 --> 11:26.351
About 20 years ago, I had the opportunity to travel with a team to Cambodia.

11:26.391 --> 11:28.373
We were looking at some potential work sites.

11:29.114 --> 11:34.219
And while we were there, there was an invitation extended to us by a Cambodian general.

11:34.919 --> 11:38.283
It turns out that some of his soldiers had found a live cobra.

11:39.184 --> 11:44.969
And while supposedly cobras were protected in Cambodia, I guess if you're a general, you can do what you want.

11:45.690 --> 11:49.874
And there was a ritual that had been around for years among the Cambodians.

11:49.986 --> 12:06.630
that if you took a living cobra and you killed it, but you took out it still beating heart and you put it into vodka and then you drank shots of the vodka with cobra blood in it, it was supposed to give you greater strength and courage.

12:07.952 --> 12:13.180
Most of us, perhaps not surprisingly, found reasons to excuse ourselves from the dinner.

12:14.862 --> 12:17.426
One of our guys, though, decided he was going to go.

12:18.178 --> 12:19.119
because you know how it is.

12:19.159 --> 12:21.582
In any group, there is always that one guy.

12:21.602 --> 12:23.624
And he was it.

12:23.664 --> 12:33.855
So he tried vodka and then ended up violently ill all night and discovered that he received absolutely no sympathy from the rest of us.

12:36.798 --> 12:42.044
Now, I have zero interest in drinking anything containing cobra blood.

12:43.766 --> 12:47.410
But I have to admit, it's easy to see how you could think

12:47.778 --> 12:52.025
that doing so might give you some kind of an extra power boost.

12:52.045 --> 12:56.793
I mean, that's a pretty powerful creature, powerful poison it, it kills.

12:58.536 --> 13:00.839
And so what doesn't kill you makes you stronger, right?

13:02.262 --> 13:06.008
But God didn't tell the children of Israel to go cobra hunting.

13:07.310 --> 13:09.213
He told them to lay hands on a lamb.

13:10.876 --> 13:14.642
I don't know anyone who is intimidated by lambs.

13:15.426 --> 13:21.052
In fact, I can't think really of a more tranquil, less dangerous creature than a lamb.

13:22.813 --> 13:27.678
If the destroyer is coming, wouldn't you want something more dangerous than a lamb protecting you?

13:29.040 --> 13:33.264
If you know your Bible, then I'm sure you recognize the important role that lambs play throughout.

13:34.405 --> 13:39.009
In the Old Testament, lambs play a central role in the religious observances of the people.

13:40.050 --> 13:43.634
Certainly in this Passover feast, the lamb was central.

13:44.130 --> 13:46.413
The lambs could be offered as sin offerings.

13:47.195 --> 13:52.843
When the high priest made his yearly offering for the sins of the nation, it was a lamb that gave up its life on the altar.

13:54.105 --> 13:58.291
And when we come to the New Testament, lambs again play this important role.

13:59.253 --> 14:03.139
When the angels announced Jesus' birth, it was to who?

14:04.240 --> 14:08.807
It was to shepherds, keeping watch over lambs by night.

14:09.829 --> 14:13.234
Many scholars are convinced because of the location

14:13.474 --> 14:23.750
where that angelic visit occurred, that these shepherds were the ones in charge of caring for the temple sanctioned flock from which the Passover lambs were selected.

14:25.392 --> 14:32.904
When John the Baptist first laid eyes on Jesus standing there at the Jordan River, you recall what he proclaimed.

14:33.846 --> 14:39.314
He said, behold, the Lamb of God who takes away the sin of the world.

14:40.866 --> 14:53.604
And later when the Apostle John had his vision, as recorded in the book of Revelation, he says that he saw standing before the throne of God a lamb that appeared to have been slain.

14:55.146 --> 14:56.528
But it was standing.

14:57.610 --> 15:02.036
It was a living lamb, even though it appears it had been put to death.

15:03.478 --> 15:08.946
And then here's the song that John heard, the host of heaven singing about the lamb.

15:09.922 --> 15:28.026
They sang a new song saying, were there you to take the scroll and to open its seals, for you were slain, and by your blood, you ransomed people for God from every tribe and language and people and nation, and you've made them a kingdom and priests to their God, and they shall reign on the earth.

15:29.888 --> 15:30.309
The Lamb.

15:32.271 --> 15:37.618
Maybe you've seen speed painters who start with a blank slate.

15:38.722 --> 15:48.237
And within a few minutes, they start smearing paint all over the canvas and what looks like just this chaotic swirl of colors.

15:52.643 --> 16:02.098
And then at the last minute, they spend the painting over and you realize the picture they've been painting all along.

16:25.442 --> 16:29.067
of what God was up to, all through the Old Testament.

16:30.409 --> 16:33.473
In bold strokes, he begins painting a picture.

16:34.354 --> 16:38.720
It's a picture that oftentimes seems dark, sometimes confusing.

16:40.102 --> 16:48.834
The worst impulses of the human heart are on full display, and with them, death and judgment lurk.

16:48.854 --> 16:54.962
But also, it's a picture where lambs oddly appear as agents of sacrifice and salvation.

16:56.450 --> 17:01.638
And then suddenly the canvas of biblical history is spun 180 degrees.

17:02.780 --> 17:04.843
And we see what he's really been painting all along.

17:06.346 --> 17:08.529
Human failure still darkens the picture.

17:09.851 --> 17:13.737
But the one who truly saves is God's lamb.

17:14.899 --> 17:19.246
Those Old Testament lambs have all been really portraits of Jesus.

17:20.949 --> 17:24.274
Now here's the thing about those upside down surprise paintings.

17:25.090 --> 17:30.517
Once you know what the painting is, once you've seen it flipped right side up, you can't unsee it.

17:31.218 --> 17:34.863
If you start the whole process over right away, you see what's going on.

17:34.983 --> 17:36.285
It makes a lot more sense.

17:37.547 --> 17:47.240
In fact, I understand there are artists who intentionally paint upside down because they feel that it helps them to see the subject even better in fresh ways.

17:49.563 --> 17:54.930
Looking through that clarifying lens, the New Testament back to that first Passover feast,

17:55.330 --> 17:57.613
You can't help but see it with fresh eyes.

17:58.835 --> 18:05.625
The people who cried out for freedom from their slavery, the people who stood in danger of death from the destroyer.

18:07.027 --> 18:10.072
And don't forget it wasn't just the Egyptians that were in danger.

18:11.414 --> 18:15.279
The Lord said the Israelites would face death as well if they ventured outside.

18:15.339 --> 18:22.951
In other words, there was nothing inherently better or stronger or more noble about them than there was the Egyptians.

18:24.132 --> 18:25.234
They were in the same

18:25.346 --> 18:25.867
Danger.

18:25.887 --> 18:50.334
In fact, if you look at the later history of Israel, and this summer we spent our time looking at the minor prophets, and you recall the minor prophets call out the children of Israel over and over again for their oppression of the poor, for their greed, for their sin, and you realize that in their hearts they were just as prone to abusing others as those who abused them.

18:50.354 --> 18:53.778
The only thing they lacked in Egypt was the power to do so.

18:55.362 --> 18:58.205
They were not spared due to their moral excellence.

18:59.807 --> 19:03.371
They were offered and escaped purely by grace.

19:04.953 --> 19:08.977
They were saved by grace through faith.

19:10.399 --> 19:14.363
They placed their faith in what Moses had told them to do with the lamb.

19:16.245 --> 19:24.434
They found the key to their freedom and the saving of their lives under the protection of a perfect lamb who gave its life for theirs.

19:25.666 --> 19:27.748
How can you not see the picture of Jesus there?

19:28.990 --> 19:32.153
A perfect one giving up his life in place of ours.

19:33.475 --> 19:43.065
And in that sacrifice offering us freedom from the things that enslave us, the promise of life, eternal life in its fullest.

19:45.207 --> 19:48.371
Of course, there's a whole sermon that could be preached on why Jesus had to die.

19:50.513 --> 19:55.058
To a lot of modern people, that sounds too extreme.

19:55.682 --> 19:57.765
It's too mystical.

19:57.885 --> 19:59.527
It's too esoteric.

19:59.567 --> 20:12.545
It's too primitive an idea to think that somehow this man dying could have a moral impact on my own life, that my wrongs could be forgiven because of his sacrifice.

20:12.625 --> 20:21.858
But I think it's only because we've been too influenced by cultural voices that have tried to strip away our sense of moral duty before God.

20:23.180 --> 20:24.562
We make too little.

20:25.282 --> 20:28.767
of the moral consequence before God of our own wrongs.

20:30.349 --> 20:38.059
We have attempted to eliminate any sense of guilt for breaking God's rules by maintaining that everybody should be free to set their own rules.

20:39.360 --> 20:40.141
You have your truth.

20:40.241 --> 20:41.063
I have my truth.

20:41.123 --> 20:42.124
We all have our own truth.

20:42.164 --> 20:46.690
As long as you're trying to live by your truth consistently, we'd like to think that that was enough.

20:49.273 --> 20:52.978
Have you ever played a game with a highly competitive five-year-old?

20:55.554 --> 20:57.697
Among my grandchildren, there are a few of those.

20:59.759 --> 21:04.024
And if you notice that if you start to win, they change the rules.

21:06.127 --> 21:07.408
You get five-year-old rules.

21:08.109 --> 21:11.714
Now, if you watch them close, you'll realize that they break their own rules.

21:12.635 --> 21:16.680
And when they do, they make new rules to cover for the rules that they just broke.

21:18.903 --> 21:25.010
When it comes to life, I think even the most avid proponent of individual freedom

21:25.538 --> 21:30.484
will still find themselves in situations where they feel cheated or wronged.

21:31.425 --> 21:41.798
In other words, they feel like there's some rule that has been broken that should have been kept and they've been left on the short end of the stick.

21:41.818 --> 21:47.324
I think we all know in our most honest moments that there is such a thing as good and evil.

21:48.586 --> 21:55.474
You may want to talk around it, but when it happens to you, you know the difference between good and evil.

21:56.866 --> 22:03.495
If there is such a thing as good, then there must be a standard greater than our own that we are liable to.

22:05.738 --> 22:11.946
And if there's a standard greater than our own, then there must be a standard setter who is above all.

22:13.187 --> 22:17.513
There is some referee bigger than us that makes the final judgment.

22:20.377 --> 22:24.562
And if we have at any point and in any way slipped

22:24.642 --> 22:31.853
are hairy little toes over the boundary line of that ultimate standard, then we have a genuine problem.

22:33.635 --> 22:40.365
The Bible says that every person who has ever lived has at some point stepped over the line.

22:41.687 --> 22:42.348
All have sinned.

22:44.431 --> 22:54.226
And while I don't much care to apply that concept to myself, I'm just honest enough to admit that it is true of me.

22:55.682 --> 23:00.329
and I have a sneaking suspicion, it might be true of you too.

23:02.933 --> 23:07.040
But the Bible also tells us that God is more than simply the final referee.

23:08.682 --> 23:15.012
He is also the ultimate source of love, which creates a genuine tension.

23:17.035 --> 23:23.826
How can the final referee who by his nature cannot ignore the final rules

23:24.610 --> 23:29.496
Do other than penalize people, people he supremely loves.

23:31.819 --> 23:38.887
The Bible's answer is that God chose not only to blow the whistle, but also to take the penalty card to himself.

23:40.850 --> 23:42.151
Is there still a mystery to this?

23:43.813 --> 23:44.474
Absolutely.

23:45.936 --> 23:52.323
If you think you can explain everything about God, I would love to hear the answer right after the service.

23:53.865 --> 23:54.546
He's big.

23:55.266 --> 23:56.167
He's bigger than we are.

23:56.227 --> 23:57.348
He is mysterious.

23:57.909 --> 24:10.281
I'm sure many of those frightened Israelites on that fateful night questioned the mechanics of how a lamb dinner and some blood on the doorpost could save them from an unseen, deadly destroyer.

24:12.083 --> 24:22.233
But whether they could explain it all or not, they grabbed hold of the hope that had been given and it worked.

24:22.253 --> 24:23.314
I don't know your story.

24:24.514 --> 24:52.338
But if you've never seriously considered the offer to surrender your life to Jesus, if you've held back because you're not really sure how it could really work, and yet your heart also feels enslaved to something that is greater than you have the power in your own strength to conquer, or hopeless despite your best efforts to find happiness on your own, could I just say,

24:53.154 --> 24:56.699
that many of us here were once where you are.

24:58.421 --> 24:59.282
But there came a time.

25:01.024 --> 25:02.506
Sometimes it came in a desperation.

25:04.189 --> 25:06.752
Sometimes it came out of careful thought.

25:08.735 --> 25:20.210
Sometimes it was because we felt a tug or a push in our hearts that mystified us, but we could only recognize it as being God, giving us a nudge.

25:21.954 --> 25:23.336
And we took that step of faith.

25:25.179 --> 25:26.761
And we discovered that it works.

25:28.944 --> 25:33.151
As I was studying this, my intention was certainly drawn to the powerful imagery of the lamb.

25:33.451 --> 25:34.913
I mean, how could it not be?

25:35.815 --> 25:37.557
But something else caught my eye as well.

25:39.039 --> 25:41.203
And that was the dinner guests.

25:42.805 --> 25:47.312
When I was running my business, I used to find myself often out on the road, out doing sales.

25:47.572 --> 25:51.538
And in the early days, smartphones were not a thing.

25:52.130 --> 25:57.137
And sitting in a restaurant by yourself is pretty boring.

25:58.018 --> 26:00.622
You can only read the menu so many times.

26:01.723 --> 26:05.669
And I figured out pretty quickly that I much preferred eating by myself in the car.

26:06.570 --> 26:07.651
I could listen to the radio.

26:08.452 --> 26:15.182
I didn't have to make awkward contact with other diners as they wondered what was socially wrong with me that nobody would have dinner with me.

26:18.106 --> 26:21.330
But it turns out that eating alone has become more and more common.

26:22.146 --> 26:26.150
maybe because smartphones have made it easier for us to tune out our surroundings.

26:27.511 --> 26:35.979
I was looking at some stats that said that online restaurant reservations for parties of one have increased by 64% since 2019.

26:38.161 --> 26:41.184
Lots and lots of people eating all by themselves.

26:42.546 --> 26:45.689
Now that doesn't mean that we are happier or more secure people.

26:47.070 --> 26:51.154
Researchers who compiled the World Happiness Report concluded that meal sharing

26:51.234 --> 26:57.080
is a stronger predictor of well-being than income or unemployment combined.

26:59.262 --> 27:06.149
You just spot the very explicit instructions that the Passover meal was not to be eaten alone.

27:07.811 --> 27:12.896
Every man shall take the lamb according to their father's houses and a lamb for a household.

27:14.417 --> 27:18.962
And if there aren't enough people in your household to eat a whole lamb, invite some neighbors.

27:19.938 --> 27:24.184
There was to be a group of you together on that night eating the lamb.

27:25.987 --> 27:31.696
I don't think that was simply a clean your plate rule that God has something against leftovers.

27:34.099 --> 27:40.228
The whole story, the wilderness journey from Egypt to the promised land is a mass migration.

27:41.450 --> 27:46.738
It is not a solo journey of people eating off of TV trays and brown sack lunches.

27:48.162 --> 27:51.966
It's not the adventure of Daniel Boone or Davy Crockett or the Lone Ranger.

27:52.046 --> 27:55.449
It is God's people together, journeying together.

27:56.770 --> 27:59.873
And you see that together principle repeated again and again.

27:59.953 --> 28:01.215
You see it in the New Testament.

28:02.436 --> 28:08.462
After the resurrection, Jesus told his disciples to go and wait together for the outpouring of the Holy Spirit.

28:10.083 --> 28:17.170
And the Holy Spirit was poured out one of the most visible effects of the Spirit's presence was a dynamic

28:17.250 --> 28:19.353
community life.

28:19.373 --> 28:25.023
Acts 2, all the believers met together in one place and shared everything they had.

28:25.083 --> 28:34.618
They worshiped together at the temple each day, met in homes for the Lord's Supper together and shared their meals with great joy and generosity together.

28:35.179 --> 28:42.130
And in each day, the Lord added to their fellowship, to their togetherness, those who were being saved.

28:45.570 --> 28:51.177
I think you all know that I have a love-hate relationship with our Sunday morning live stream.

28:53.319 --> 28:54.861
COVID pushed us into that world.

28:55.962 --> 29:01.148
Quite honestly, one of the last things on my list of life goals was to ever become a TV preacher.

29:03.871 --> 29:07.115
But I also appreciate the blessing it is for many.

29:08.076 --> 29:12.882
For some of you that are watching the service this morning and because of health issues,

29:12.962 --> 29:21.213
You can't be here or because people are traveling or some folks that live far away and yet tune in and get some teaching from this.

29:21.273 --> 29:22.935
And that's great.

29:23.356 --> 29:27.061
I am super glad that we're able to offer that.

29:28.442 --> 29:40.178
But I regularly hear stories of people who have given up regular personal involvement in a local fellowship and have substituted for it a curated list of

29:40.258 --> 29:50.848
YouTube favorite preachers and musicians, which is nothing more than the drive-through restaurant dining version of church.

29:52.890 --> 29:55.132
You whizz through with as little a connection as possible.

29:56.193 --> 29:59.917
You pick from the menu, whatever strikes your fancy, and then you race on to the next thing.

30:01.879 --> 30:09.266
I mentioned Sunday mornings because it's an easy place to make the point, but what I'm getting at is more than just Sunday church attendance.

30:10.434 --> 30:14.179
You can show up on a Sunday morning and turn that into a drive-through experience as well.

30:15.320 --> 30:17.743
You can rush in late just in time to catch the sermon.

30:18.023 --> 30:26.493
You can be lying out as soon as the final song starts, and you can avoid anything more than an obligatory smile to one of the ushers at the door.

30:26.533 --> 30:36.946
If you're gonna make the journey with Jesus deep and successful, you need traveling companions.

30:38.498 --> 30:40.882
There need to be other people with you at the table.

30:42.364 --> 30:59.930
You need to give time regularly to be with other Christians, to spend time in God's Word, to spend time in prayer, to spend time getting to know each other well enough that you know how to serve each other, and you know how to care for each other when you're hurting.

31:02.374 --> 31:05.138
Let me just give you three practical suggestions.

31:06.466 --> 31:11.555
One, I would say make in-person attendance on Sunday a priority.

31:12.496 --> 31:15.121
Not the thing you do if you can't think of anything else.

31:17.084 --> 31:18.386
And then don't rush out.

31:19.508 --> 31:21.531
In fact, make some space.

31:22.733 --> 31:26.540
Make some space to invite someone to go to lunch with you after the service.

31:27.782 --> 31:32.530
Have something extra on the stove at home that it'd be easy to invite someone over.

31:33.314 --> 31:35.016
Over the years, Burnett and I have learned to do that.

31:35.036 --> 31:40.502
There are Sundays that we say each other before we get to church, hey, we should find someone that we go to lunch with afterwards.

31:41.383 --> 31:45.228
We're extending what's happening here to build more community.

31:47.030 --> 31:50.133
And then third, I would say get into a life group.

31:50.153 --> 31:56.100
If you're not in some kind of a rarely meeting Bible study group, home fellowship group, you should be.

31:56.480 --> 31:58.002
And we have a lot of them.

31:58.338 --> 32:03.765
Pastor Lance does a wonderful job of helping those groups get together and get organized.

32:03.845 --> 32:07.069
And if you're not in one, talk to Lance about that.

32:07.189 --> 32:07.850
Get in one.

32:09.752 --> 32:13.537
All right, the third thing I want us to look at is the dinner dress code.

32:15.019 --> 32:27.474
This stood out to me as I was reading over these Passover instructions because not only were they told what to eat, and not only were they told with whom they were to eat, they're also told how to dress for dinner.

32:28.450 --> 32:31.234
and the instructions are really strange.

32:31.935 --> 32:32.736
Here's what it says.

32:33.397 --> 32:41.248
In this manner you shall eat it with your belt fastened, your sandals on your feet, your staff in your hand, and you shall eat in haste.

32:41.889 --> 32:43.791
It is the Lord's Passover.

32:45.514 --> 32:47.116
Now just think about the situation.

32:48.397 --> 32:49.159
It's nighttime.

32:50.080 --> 32:53.685
You're about to eat the final meal of the day.

32:54.926 --> 32:57.490
All that's left after dinner is going to bed.

32:59.554 --> 33:04.041
You have strict instructions too that you're not to leave the house all night on penalty of death.

33:04.081 --> 33:07.246
In other words, you're not going anyplace tonight.

33:08.808 --> 33:16.039
And of course, the culture of the day dictates that you leave your shoes, your sandals at the door before you enter the house.

33:16.099 --> 33:17.962
You never wear your shoes in the house.

33:19.525 --> 33:24.973
And so given that environment, what would be the appropriate attire for dinner?

33:26.435 --> 33:28.178
Maybe slippers for dinner?

33:29.282 --> 33:31.644
Something comfortable?

33:33.126 --> 33:36.749
Certainly I'm going to loosen my belt, because I know what happens when I have dinner.

33:39.172 --> 33:44.957
Maybe something really comfy, like even a robin pajamas, because you know that bedtime is next.

33:46.659 --> 33:49.341
I see people that show up at Walmart dressed that way in the middle of the day.

33:49.381 --> 33:58.290
But instead, they're told

33:58.786 --> 34:00.028
to put on traveling clothes.

34:01.670 --> 34:02.772
Cinch up your belt.

34:04.355 --> 34:05.256
Get your shoes on.

34:06.578 --> 34:08.581
Have your walking stick in your hand.

34:08.922 --> 34:13.148
The text actually says your staff, which probably means it was more than just a walking stick.

34:13.228 --> 34:15.632
It was the shepherd's tool to herd sheep and goats.

34:15.712 --> 34:16.914
So you're ready to go to work.

34:17.555 --> 34:19.738
And then wolf your dinner down.

34:21.120 --> 34:22.142
Eat in haste.

34:24.105 --> 34:27.410
In other words, don't eat this meal like you're setting in for a long winter's night.

34:27.810 --> 34:30.995
You're supposed to eat it like your morning alarm didn't go off and you're late for work.

34:32.998 --> 34:37.064
Imagine the odd scene, these folks sitting at the dinner table.

34:37.124 --> 34:38.086
It's dark outside.

34:38.126 --> 34:42.652
They know they need to stay in, but there they sit, fully dressed for work.

34:43.654 --> 34:50.104
Shepherd staffs in one hand, fork in the other, chomping down their dinner exactly the way their mother always told them not to eat.

34:52.788 --> 34:54.290
So what does that imagery tell us?

34:55.714 --> 35:03.385
Well, it tells us that God was saving His people for a journey, and He wanted them to be ready to move out at the first opportunity.

35:04.947 --> 35:09.032
That household protected by the blood of the Lamb was not the destination.

35:10.414 --> 35:12.297
It was only this starting line.

35:13.819 --> 35:24.914
If there's been a mistake that we've made in the American church, oftentimes in evangelism, we have treated it as though a person coming to Jesus, going to the old Billy Graham crusade and walking the aisle,

35:25.250 --> 35:26.311
and signing the card.

35:26.331 --> 35:28.954
We've acted as though that was the destination.

35:30.056 --> 35:30.556
It's not.

35:31.377 --> 35:33.720
It's just the start of the journey.

35:35.562 --> 35:38.526
It's a good image to keep in mind as we start the Christian life.

35:39.507 --> 35:42.431
Placing our faith in Jesus is not the end of the story.

35:43.772 --> 35:48.618
The point of being a Christian is not simply a decision to believe, it is a decision to follow.

35:50.100 --> 35:51.922
The blood of Jesus saves us.

35:53.410 --> 35:57.494
But then his spirit fills us and he calls us to move out.

35:58.995 --> 36:05.942
And coming to faith, we must come to the cross, but we must not stop there.

36:07.643 --> 36:20.676
Mark chapter eight, calling the crowd to him with his disciples, he said to them, if anyone would come after me, let him deny himself and take up his cross and follow me.

36:22.177 --> 36:23.058
We are called

36:23.458 --> 36:23.978
to a journey.

36:25.280 --> 36:26.421
It is a journey with a cross.

36:27.302 --> 36:35.349
There are sacrifices that will be made not just as our Jesus made that sacrifice, but as we follow Him, there will be sacrifices in life.

36:36.751 --> 36:37.391
It is a journey.

36:39.153 --> 36:44.658
In the coming weeks, we're going to join the Israelites as they make their way from Egypt to the Promised Land.

36:44.678 --> 36:48.762
And we're going to see that it was a long journey to get to their promised home.

36:50.043 --> 36:52.946
There was a journey that had both victories and defeats,

36:53.858 --> 36:58.146
It had triumphs, it had failures, lots of failures.

36:59.949 --> 37:02.594
But like every journey, there was a starting point.

37:04.417 --> 37:14.074
That night of Passover marked the threshold of that journey, a threshold that was marked by the blood of a lamb sacrificed so that they could be saved.

37:15.877 --> 37:18.482
It was a journey that we're called to make together.

37:19.874 --> 37:24.542
And in a journey that they were to be focused and ready to undertake on a moment's notice.

37:27.927 --> 37:33.817
So how well does that powerful imagery of Passover reflect your own journey?

37:35.199 --> 37:40.047
What would you put in your travel log about your own walk with God?

37:42.431 --> 37:46.738
Have you honestly investigated and committed your life to Jesus?

37:47.874 --> 37:54.866
The one the Bible says is God's lamb, lovingly given for our freedom and life.

37:56.909 --> 38:04.141
If you have embraced what Jesus has done for you, have you also embraced a core of like-minded people to journey with?

38:06.144 --> 38:10.492
Are you prioritizing that relationship?

38:10.512 --> 38:14.418
And if you start with the journey, what's on your feet?

38:16.034 --> 38:17.777
Are you wearing slippers or boots?

38:19.700 --> 38:20.481
What's in your hand?

38:22.023 --> 38:25.168
Is it a staff or a remote control?

38:28.073 --> 38:29.495
There is a long journey ahead.

38:31.358 --> 38:32.039
Let's get started.

38:33.161 --> 38:33.581
Let's pray.

38:37.948 --> 38:38.629
Father, thank you.

38:40.352 --> 38:41.874
Thank you for providing the lamb.

38:44.706 --> 39:00.206
Lord Jesus, thank you for being willing to be the sacrifice that we have all needed for giving us freedom, a way to begin the journey out of slavery into true life.

39:02.049 --> 39:05.093
Thank you that you've not called us to make the journey alone.

39:05.113 --> 39:06.374
You have given us your spirit.

39:06.414 --> 39:09.298
You've given us brothers and sisters to share the journey with.

39:11.810 --> 39:15.796
Lord, I pray for any of my friends here this morning that have not yet started that journey.

39:17.680 --> 39:25.472
Father, I pray that they would hear how much you love them and how free and open the offer is.

39:25.512 --> 39:38.994
For those of us who have responded, Lord, I pray that if we are sitting there with our slippers and remote control, that you would give us the nudge that we need to get up and follow you with a full heart.

39:40.802 --> 39:46.056
Lord, I'm convinced that what you have set in front of us is a beautiful, promised land.

39:47.439 --> 39:51.470
Help us, Lord, not to miss out on the journey with you.

39:51.490 --> 39:54.919
I pray this in Jesus' name.

39:55.741 --> 39:56.242
Amen.

